Ask John: Office romances have their pitfalls but you might still meet Mr or Mrs Right
Straight-talking, common sense from the front line of management
'Company rule books can’t control physical attraction.' Photo: REX	By John Timpson
5:12PM GMT 26 Jan 2014
Comments
Q One of my staff recently sent me a message on an online dating website. I was initially embarrassed but must admit that I do think he is very attractive. Is this a terrible idea? If so, how do I deal with the whole issue? A Company rule books can’t control physical attraction. It’s entirely up to you whether to go on the date but you may be heading for disaster.
It isn’t surprising so many relationships start through work. I know of 13 couples, currently employed in our office, and many Timpson shops such as Alfreton and Harlow are run by long term partners. But a few facets of your question give cause for concern.
You have to wonder why he made the contact online – didn’t he have the courage to declare his intentions face to face? You say he is “one of my staff” so I assume you’re his boss. It’s not a good idea to date a member of your own team. Others are bound to suspect favouritism especially if you work in the same part of the building and irritatingly gaze starry eyed across the office and hold hands as you go to the canteen together for lunch. If your relationship ends, life at the office could become so tricky that one of you will have to leave the business.
Related Articles
If you feel your pregnant colleague is not playing fair, tell her
10 Nov 2013
Apprenticeships are fine, but the devil will be in the detail if government gets involved
01 Dec 2013
When love flows at the water cooler
27 Sep 2012
Is office romance a source of workplace heartache?
19 Apr 2011
Think carefully before making a move, I’ve listed a lot of the pitfalls but there’s always the chance this is the man for you. Plenty of company romances confound the critics and blossom into a life-changing partnership. My father met my mother in our office at Kettering. But he didn’t make his first move over the internet.
Q The media is suggesting there will be a large influx of Bulgarians and Romanians into the UK in 2014. Where will they find work? Did you recruit any Poles when a similar situation arose from Poland joining the EU in 2004? A We discriminate in two ways. We have pledged to recruit 10pc of our workforce from prison and we only choose applicants who “get it”. You could say we discriminate against weaker candidates.
We always try to pick people with personality, they come in all shapes and sizes. As a result the men and women who join us include Geordies, Poles, Cockneys, Somalians, Italians, Scousers, Scots, West Indians, Irish, Romanians, Welsh and Chinese – lots of nationalities with a wide range of accents who all speak our language.
Everyone starts as an apprentice so it is much easier for us to teach people with good English. Consequently, British born applicants have a built in advantage but I bet some Bulgarians and Romanians will become Timpson colleagues during 2014.
Q I work for a company as a sales rep but, after two years, they still haven’t come up with a commission offer despite working extra hours. How do you reward your sales staff? A We have a bonus scheme that hasn’t changed for over 20 years. We use the same system in each shop every week of the year.
All wages paid to anyone working at the shop that week are added up and multiplied by 4.5 to produce a sales target (we use 4.5 because it works!).
All sales over the target earn a 15pc bonus, which is paid out the following Thursday. The bonus is only given to colleagues there during the week, people on holiday or off sick don’t qualify. The payout is shared according to experience. Our training is linked to skill tests, with every pass earning an extra point. Colleagues with the most points earn the biggest bonus.
That system, which I hope sounds as simple as it really is, provides the adrenalin that puts a buzz into our business. It makes sure most of our colleagues are keen to look after their customers and hopefully helps to give our customers a better service.
It certainly works for us and may well work for lots of other businesses.
Q My friend applied for one of the Government’s Start Up Loans and spent it on a car and a holiday. The loan provider didn’t seem to care. Do you think that this whole wheeze is in fact being used as a secret form of quantitative easing?
A I would be surprised if the Government has a Machiavellian plan but Start Up Loans can clearly help to pep up the economy. I have never really understood quantitative easing (I just hope Mark Carney does) but, in a world where banks are so risk-averse, it must be right for the Government to step in and help budding entrepreneurs. Every government spends some of our taxes on business schemes that fill a political agenda but don’t necessarily have a commercial benefit. My big beef is about training. Sadly, too much of the billions spent on apprenticeships fails to find its way to the shop floor. By squandering his loan your friend wasted his opportunity as well as some taxpayer’s money (despite the red tape put in place to protect the public purse). This was probably caused by preferring process to personality. Start Up Loans shouldn’t be awarded on the basis of a business plan, they should simply back the right people. Even if your friend had a great plan on paper, they picked the wrong man.
