Social services 'failed to protect teenager from years of family abuse'
Exclusive: Social services failed to protect a teenager from years of family abuse and violence, despite dozens of “very significant” warnings that the girl was at risk of harm, an independent review has concluded. The council's social services department was ranked as "inadequate" by Ofsted - the same verdict given to Haringey, the council that failed Baby P, pictured. Photo: PA	By Andrew Hough, and Matthew Holehouse
7:30AM GMT 11 Mar 2011
Comments
A catalogue of failures by Essex County Council over almost two decades caused “Agnes” to be unnecessarily subjected to physical and sexual abuse by her mother and relatives, the damning report found. A serious case review, conducted by the Essex Safeguarding Children’s Board, heavily criticised social services for failing to make risk assessments on Agnes their “prime focus”, The Daily Telegraph can disclose. Agnes, who cannot be identified for legal reasons, was neglected and physically or sexually abused by her mother, her mother’s partners and her step-grandfather throughout her childhood and teenage years. But social services failed to act, despite being “overwhelmed” with at least 200 warnings, from concerned neighbours and her older siblings. Many of these warnings were deemed “very significant” and all would have required official investigation, the review concluded. Related Articles
Social workers had 50 chances to save boy killed by father
05 Sep 2012
Baby P council offers £140,000 for 'place and sustainability' director
10 Mar 2011
Local taxpayers are left powerless when councils cut the wrong services
09 Mar 2011
Ombudsman could investigate child 'snatching' by courts
06 Mar 2011
Mother who bought son cannabis speaks of anguish
27 Feb 2011
Social services took my children
26 Feb 2011
The report, obtained by this newspaper, found that when officials did become involved, assessments on the abused child were initially left to students. The council last night admitted that no staff member or officials had been disciplined or had “any further action” taken against them following the blunders. Agnes, the youngest of several siblings – all of whom had been abused in some form - was placed into care in her mid teens in 2006 after she told police about her abuse. Before the family, none of whom can be named, moved to the area in 1990, they had already been known to social services in other parts of the country. But despite several years of involvement officials failed to raise concerns about why the family were no longer being monitored. It also found that while there was a history of abuse in the family, risk assessments on Agnes were "never the prime focus” for social services. The report found social workers wrongly thought Agnes would be better protected because several of her mother’s children had already been taken into care. An executive summary of the review into Agnes treatment, written in November 2010 last year but published several months later, also found that: * Risks of physical violence were either never considered or viewed as “peripheral” despite more than 30 incidents of harm involving her mother including assaulting police and doctors who visited her home. * Officials never questioned Ms T’s claims that Agnes “bruised easily”, which was used to “cover-up” the physical abuse. They also prioritised her mother's needs over the children’s while officials felt “sorry” for Ms T, who was violent and depressed. * Sexual abuse was “partially recognised” but rarely acted upon while domestic violence was never fully addressed. * No man who had contact with the family was subjected to background checks despite most known to police as being a danger. * Neglect to Agnes was never assessed despite medical evidence of poor growth and obesity. Bob Cook, the report’s author, said he wanted to understand why “Agnes remained in her mother’s care for so long” despite two decades of social services’ involvement and “very significant concerns” raised about the family. “The sheer volumes of concerns at some points in this case… must have led to a feeling of front line staff being overwhelmed,” he wrote. “The lack of strategic management response through the history of this case is one of the most striking features. "There were specific decisions raising questions of competence of some specialist staff."
Mr Crow called for better monitoring, communication and tighter control over cases that would be “sufficiently robust” to address the multiple failings. Last year its social services department was ranked as “inadequate” by Ofsted - the same verdict given to Haringey, the council that failed Baby P. A council spokeswoman admitted that no one had been disciplined from the case. “We are satisfied that there is no further disciplinary action arising from this case,” she said. She also admitted the review found social services were “focused too much on helping the mother”, in what she claimed was to help “improve her parenting skills”. “When it was becoming increasingly clear that this approach was not working, and not enough on safeguarding the children,” she added. But she denied up to 200 “warnings” were “ignored”. “The issue here is not that these incidents were ignored, but that they were not taken as cumulative evidence that a child protection enquiry was necessary,” she said. “In fact, this family received a lot of social work time and attention and were closely monitored for long periods.” The case was now used as training material, she added. She said it was publicly released “earlier than it should have been”. Children's Health
