Numbers don't add up, but VW Polo is still the winner
If you believe a car is the second most expensive thing in your life, after a house, you are wrong...
Home comforts: VW claims cars are less expensive than we might think, but its evidence is flimsy
Photo: ALAMY	By Mike Rutherford
11:25AM BST 20 Sep 2010
Comments
That, at least, is VW’s view. The German giant has started producing contentious statistics to support its claim that cars are number five on our lifetime expenditure lists.
The firm makes a lot of generalisations and assumptions when trying to prove VWs are comparatively inexpensive.
It estimates the average Brit spends £1,785,264 during their lifetime, but I’m not sure how Mr or Mrs Average gets close. Volkswagen is sticking with that figure, though. Housing is the top item on the list, with a total figure of £835,588, at today’s prices. Of that, £645,078 pays for the home, another £98,580 goes on domestic energy while £91,930 takes care of creature comforts. All this equates to 47 per cent of the £1.8 million lifetime spend, the Germans say. Second comes food and drink, 18 per cent or £314,128 of our cash. Of that, £182,687 goes on food shopping, £91,539 on “dining” (eating in restaurants) and £39,902 on drinking. Related Articles
Electric cars make sense
01 Oct 2010
40pc off your new car
09 Sep 2010
Tax-free cars: ten golden rules for buying a dream car
26 Aug 2010
Tax-free cars: phenomenal deals for the drivers who ship abroad
26 Aug 2010
Tax-free cars: where to find a bargain
26 Aug 2010
Buying a car doesn't have to be taxing
02 Jun 2010
Having “fun” has a price tag of £287,514, or 16 per cent of your lifetime spend. Think £134,963 for going out, £34,458 for hobbies and £118,093 for clothes (which I’d have put on the “essential” list, personally).
Holidays are fourth and cost £136,397, or eight per cent, with £112,708 on annual breaks, £15,075 on weekends away and only £8,614 on days out. Volkswagen argues that cars are a lowly fifth - and last - in terms of big-league spending. At least, they are if they are VW Polos.
Buy them new, own and run each one until their warranties expire three years later and their “lifetime cost” will be £127,630, seven per cent of the average total expenditure over 80 years. But hang on - to stick to that comparatively low figure, we’re only buying 10 Polos, and keeping each for three years.
Generally though, keen, healthy drivers are likely to run cars for 60 years rather than 30, aren’t they? VW’s figure must surely be doubled to £255,260 if it’s to have any credibility. True, this means paying more than £250,000 on buying, owning and running modest, but newish, VW Polos.
A less painful and more productive way of looking at it is to acknowledge that the Polo ownership/usership figure per year is just £4,254. Do 12,000 miles a year and this works out at little more than 30p per mile. Correctly, VW is keen to point out that Polos are cheap to buy outright (from £9,790), refuel (petrol versions do 50mpg on the Combined cycle, diesels 80mpg), service (£250 for a 36-month package deal) and hold their value (most depreciating less than 50 per cent in three years). While I have doubts about VW’s expenditure claims, I can’t quibble with what it says about the Polo. If you’re looking to spend about £10,000, it is undoubtedly the best car available. Mike Rutherford
