Alistair Darling: Alex Salmond is misleading Scots about the cost of independence
Alistair Darling has warned Alex Salmond is misleading Scots about the financial cost of leaving the UK after the White Paper on independence included only one “scanty” page of estimates. Alistair Darling has said Alex Salmond is taking Scots 'for a ride' Photo: DAVID CHESKIN/PA	By Simon Johnson, Scottish Political Editor
4:12PM GMT 27 Nov 2013
Comments
The former Chancellor said he was “very, very angry” at the paucity of figures in the Scottish Government’s 670-page White Paper, published on Tuesday, and suggested that Mr Salmond was attempting to take his countrymen “for a ride”. He said the document’s page of projections outlining a newly separate Scotland’s finances in 2016/17 was so flimsy that it appeared to have been written on the back of an envelope on a kitchen table. While the White Paper suggested that a separate Scotland’s national debt interest payments could start at £3.9 billion a year, he warned this figure could easily reach £9 billion if the SNP’s “optimistic” assumptions were not realised. Mr Darling contrasted the document with the Red Book produced by the Treasury at every Budget, the most recent of which contained 112 pages of tax and revenue projections, and said Mr Salmond “should not be allowed to get away with it”. The leader of the pro-UK Better Together campaign spoke out after Mr Salmond’s spokesman claimed that Scottish separation would be “cost neutral” despite having to create new government departments and armed forces. Related Articles
Scottish ministers threatened with legal action over 'state guardian' plans
19 Feb 2014
Nicola Sturgeon: Economy will decide independence referendum
03 Jan 2014
Independent Scotland's taxpayers 'face £1.6 billion bill for only three of Alex Salmond's spending promises'
18 Dec 2013
Business leaders criticise Alex Salmond's independence 'wish lists'
11 Dec 2013
Nationalist anger at supermarkets over independence food price warning
10 Dec 2013
Downing Street hunt over Alistair Darling whispering campaign
05 Dec 2013
The White Paper contained no price tag for creating a Scottish state, although a leaked paper by John Swinney, the Scottish Finance Minister, admitted that the cost of tax collection alone could more than double to £625 million. Although the document made a series of major spending promises, including a major expansion of childcare, none were costed and it ignored a report by the Institute for Fiscal Studies that an extra £6 billion of savings would have to be found. Speaking at a press conference in Edinburgh, Mr Darling said: “You would have thought when setting out something that was called a prospectus for a blueprint for Scotland’s future, you would have had more than one page and a pretty scanty page at that. “This is back of envelope stuff. This is something you do at the kitchen table – maybe that’s what happened to it on Saturday night before it finally went to the printers.”
The former Chancellor added: “Just look at the Red Book and the sort of things that’s in it and look at this one page and ask yourself is Alex Salmond taking the people of Scotland seriously? It just looks like he is taking us for a ride.” According to the White Paper, total Scottish spending in 2016/17 will be £63.7 billion but Mr Darling said this took no account of the costs of setting up a new state. The document said the interest on the national debt would be £3.9 billion if the latter was calculated using the balance between tax and spending since 1980/81, which coincides with the boom years of North Sea oil. The former Chancellor said an alternative figure of £5.5 billion, based on Scotland’s GDP share of the UK national debt, would be more likely. But he said the White Paper failed to take into account that a new and smaller nation state would pay higher interest on its debt, with an independent economic think tank estimating the additional cost being between £1 billion and £2.2 billion. Mr Darling said the document assumes North Sea oil will generate between £6.8 billion and £7.9 billion, whereas the independent Office for Budget Responsibility put the figure at £4.3 billion. The net result is a separate Scotland would start life making £9 billion of interest payments on its debt, he estimated, a higher proportion of its GDP (5.2 per cent) than the UK. Nicola Sturgeon, the Deputy First Minister, said: “Alistair Darling’s rattled and feeble response to the White Paper says it all – the No campaign are rapidly running out of ideas, and have nothing positive to say.”
Meanwhile, David Mr Cameron told Prime Minister’s Questions that the White Paper was a thick document full of false promise” that had left a “huge set of questions” on a separate Scotland’s currency and Nato and EU membership. “In the absence of any detailed costings, it wasn't a blueprint for independence but a wish list,” he said. Politics
