High-speed rail route 'under threat' as Tories refuse to support Labour's proposals
A high-speed train link from London to Birmingham is to become a political battleground after the Conservatives refused to support Labour’s proposals. Lord Adonis, the transport secretary, has previously cautioned that the multi-billion pound project will not succeed unless it is 'above politics'. Photo: HEATHCLIFFE O'MALLEY	By Nick Collins
7:30AM GMT 19 Feb 2010
Follow Both Labour and the Tories support plans for a 200mph route from the capital to the Midlands but are expected to clash over which communities will be affected. The Tories have refused offers to see an advanced copy of the white paper on the project. The white paper will detail the location of the tracks – which is expected to pass through Buckinghamshire and parts of the Chilterns – to within five metres in urban areas and within 25 metres in the countryside. The Conservatives want to leave their options open so that an alternative route could be drawn up if they win the general election. The party has commissioned a team of independent rail experts to look over the proposals, which were drawn up by High Speed Two, a public company. They have not yet seen the final report. Lord Adonis, the transport secretary, has previously cautioned that the multi-billion pound project will not succeed unless it is “above politics”. Theresa Villiers, the shadow transport secretary, said the Conservatives had turned down the chance to see the final report on the proposals before they were published.
She said it would be “inappropriate” to make a decision without consulting people along the route. She told The Guardian: “We are not going to give a political blank cheque to Labour. “We would not want to close down debate on a route before the people affected by it have the chance to be heard. It would be very unfair for the people affected if they thought there was a cosy political consensus on the route.” The Conservatives have promised to develop a high-speed line between London and Birmingham instead of a third runway at Heathrow, and are believed to be in favour of making Heathrow central to the route. Lord Adonis said: “Full public consultation will of course take place on any route proposed by the government. The consensus I seek is on the principle of high-speed rail, so that it can be taken forward on a cross-party basis in the next parliament.” Road and rail transport
