Baghdad liquor shop owner toasts the Green Zone
By Adrian Blomfield in Baghdad
12:01AM BST 22 Apr 2005
Finding a beer in Baghdad can be a challenge these days, what with the bombs and the rising Islamic militancy. But one off-licence in the Iraqi capital is going from strength to strength. Sa'ad Sabah, its proprietor, has become one of the city's most successful small businessmen. Within range of United States armour and watchtowers lining the blast walls of the Green Zone, his shop, The Rose, attracts customers from the suburbs. Mr Sabah has little competition largely because Islamic extremists now register their disapproval of alcohol by bombing his rivals' premises. The Rose, however, is unscathed, presumably because the bombers fear the proximity of US military hardware. Despite living in the shadow of what many Iraqis regard as occupiers, Mr Sabah insists that he is not a collaborator. But he does admit to profiting unwittingly from his competitors' misfortune. "When the other shops closed, I shut for only two days," he said. "Since then sales have gone up by at least 50 per cent. I'm still nervous, I'm still afraid. But I do believe that being so close to the Green Zone will keep us fairly safe."
Related Articles
Oil-for-food pair quit over
22 Apr 2005
Above the rows of vodka and cheap whisky, stands a shrine to his father, like him a Kurdish Christian, who founded the shop in 1971. Underneath his photograph are the words: "Love one another as I have loved you." Seeking to do just that, he has encouraged rivals whose businesses had been destroyed to set up shop nearby. There are now five off-licences within 300 yards and the street has become known as Alcohol Alley. Before the war business was good. The Koran forbade the consumption of alcohol but Muslims who chose to drink were indulged by a regime that was, for the most part, religiously liberal. The vast majority of visitors to Alcohol Alley today are still Muslim. But intimidation from the extremists necessitates discretion. Iraqis caught with alcohol risk kidnapping or execution. But Alcohol Alley is now fearful for its future. The new government is dominated by Shia politicians with ties to conservative clerics. "We are very concerned about the new government," Mr Sabah said. "It is possible they could ban alcohol.'' Iraq
