Sharpen your focus with Babbel’s online language courses
Studying a new language or brushing up on an old one can have a positive effect on the brain. It has also been linked with staving off the effects of dementia
Babbel makes learning a language enjoyable and pressure free By Hazel Davis
5:07PM BST 08 Aug 2013
Being Scandinavian is just about the best thing to be at the moment. In fact, most of my decisions (baby clothes, breakfast items, TV viewing choices) are currently made using the question, “What would the Scandinavians do?” What they would do, undoubtedly, is embrace the idea that learning a language can boost your wellbeing. A couple of years ago researchers from York University in Canada found that speaking two languages has a positive effect on the brain, sharpening focus and even staving off the effects of dementia. My own previously sharp mind has taken a bit of a battering lately, what with juggling work and babies and all. So, in the interests of self-improvement and in a nod to the fact that my other half looks a bit like a Viking, I sign up to an online language course from Babbel. To get some focus. Fjord focus. Babbel offers 13 languages at various levels. To assess my suitability I take an introductory test, after which the site gently suggests I might want to start with beginner’s Norwegian at £8.95 a month (much cheaper than signing up to a “real-life” class). Related Articles
Stay the course
02 Dec 2013
The really great thing about this site is it won’t let you get a question wrong
You can choose to do the course with or without speech recognition, which means you can practise in a café with no embarrassment or out loud in your bedroom while the dog looks on pityingly. Norwegian, the site tells me, has two forms; the literary language, Bokmål, and New Norwegian (Nynorsk) and children learn both at school. I am learning the book language. I’m a bit worried that this won’t equip me to ask for more rakfisk but I plough on. I also learn that there is no standard dialect as everyone speaks his or her own and everyone understands. The exercises are easy to start with. I get 78 per cent for my pronunciation of hei (hello), thank you very much. Then I have to fill in the missing letters in a sentence such as “Hei Lars”. It sounds childish but, you know what, it really sinks in. Filling in the blanks gets progressively harder and I get less cocky. Under each question there are little tips such as, “In older Norwegian texts it’s not uncommon to see aa written for the letter å for example. Håkon or mål (goal) as maal.” The really great thing about this site is it won’t let you get a question wrong, so there’s no ill-feeling between you and the machine. The blank simply remains silently red until you have got it right. Moreover, it knows I full well know what a personal pronoun is and what the different tenses are and does not condescend, but at the same time it also lets me listen 27 times to a lady saying, “God morgen, Per” (Good morning, Per) without judging me. You can pick and choose sections too, so that if one day you fancy skipping forward to ordering something in a café or if you want to go back to the section about pronouncing ø and o, you can (it’s a relief to have finally cleared that up). I swear I’m not making this up but after just a few days of regular practice, I do find myself thinking slightly differently. When I read, I read in a different way. It’s as though I am paying more attention, listening harder to people. I feel proud of myself, like I am achieving something. And I also now know how to say Jo Nesbø properly. Start learning a new language online with Babbel. It's fast, fun and fully interactive. Try for free today. Learn A New Language
