Pep Guardiola dons lederhosen after Bayern Munich leapfrog Borussia Dortmund in Bundesliga
The Spanish manager celebrated Bayern's recent success with a squad trip to the Oktoberfest beer festival.
Beer we go: Pep Guardiola celebrates Bayern Munich's recent run of form Photo: AP PHOTO	By Telegraph Sport
11:28PM BST 06 Oct 2013
Follow Comments
Spain
Atletico Madrid’s Brazilian-born striker Diego Costa will heed a call-up from Spain. Costa is leading scorer in La Liga with 10 goals but is ineligible for the forthcoming qualifiers against Belarus and Georgia due to a paperwork delay. “I have played my entire career here regardless that I was born in Brazil,” Costa said. “Spain has given me everything and if I can play for the national team I will do it as well as I can.” The forward turns 25 today and celebrated with both goals in a 2-1 win against Celta Vigo to give Atletico a record eighth successive win. Barcelona remained top on goal difference after beating Valladolid 4-1 but Real Madrid required a deflected strike from Cristiano Ronaldo in the last minute to see off Levante. Marko Marin, on loan from Chelsea, set up Sevilla’s winner as they beat Almeria. Germany
Table-topping Bayern Munich celebrated their recent success as their Spanish manager Pep Guardiola took the squad to the Oktoberfest beer festival. The former Barcelona coach, accompanied by his wife Christina, even donned the traditional lederhosen and hat for the occasion on Sunday. Bayern had leapfrogged Borussia Dortmund to go top of the Bundesliga on Saturday after drawing 1-1 with Bayer Leverkusen. Bayern Chairman Karl-Heinz Rummenigge told the players: “Celebrate freely. Our next game isn’t for another two weeks. We can enjoy the beer.” There was little cause for jubilation for Dortmund manager Jürgen Klopp, however. His side were defeated 2-0 by Borussia Monchengladbach, losing Nuri Sahin and Sven Bender to injury. Italy
