Mike De Kock puts Soft Falling Rain's unbeaten record on the line in Newbury's Hungerford Stakes
Top trainers are busy characters, bustling from gallops to office to racecourse, all the time keeping in contact with their owners and staff, forever in search of the next big winner.
Seven up: Soft Falling Rain lands the Godolphin Mile at Meydan Photo: AFP	By HOTSPUR (J A McGrath)
5:47PM BST 14 Aug 2013
Comments
But Mike De Kock, the South African champion, takes that frenetic daily schedule to new levels. De Kock, having recently collected the trainers’ title for the eighth time in his native country, also has a large squad of horses in Dubai and keeps a satellite yard in Newmarket for the horses his owners purchase in this part of the world. No surprise then that De Kock has several quality horses on the go there at this time of the year and in the next week punters can look forward to seeing two of his best, Soft Falling Rain, who will make his British debut in Newbury’s Hungerford Stakes on Saturday, and Shea Shea in York’s Nunthorpe Stakes on Aug 23. The unbeaten Soft Falling Rain looked very classy when he landed the Godolphin Mile at Meydan on Dubai World Cup night in March, extending his winning sequence to seven. He has not run since and De Kock warned yesterday that there would still be something to work on. “He is going to improve with this run,” he said. “You can’t get them 101 per cent first up, but he’s as fit as I can get him without a race. We’ll see how he comes out of it, and then we might look at the Prix de la Foret, at Longchamp, on Arc weekend. He likes the Tapeta surface at Meydan, and also fast ground on turf.”
It is interesting that having won the UAE 2,000 Guineas and the Godolphin Mile, that connections feel the colt will be better placed coming back a furlong for his next two outings. Related Articles
