British and Irish Lions 2013: the issues facing coach Warren Gatland as selection D-day looms
From team selection to claims of bias, Warren Gatland has much to ponder over 48 hours.
Wing and a prayer: had Simon Zebo been fit throughout the Six Nations you suspect there would not be so much argument about his inclusion on the Lions tour Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Steve James
10:00PM BST 27 Apr 2013
Follow Comments
Captaincy He is the only player that will be present at the Hilton London, Syon Park when the squad is announced at 11am on Tuesday and so will be the only one with any advance knowledge of selection. All other players will discover the squad at the same time as the rest of us. It boiled down to a choice between Paul O’Connell and Sam Warburton, with Brian O’Driscoll, Jamie Heaslip and Chris Robshaw all considered before slipping out of contention. It is understood that Warburton will pip O’Connell. In that case, it will be very much a case of head coach Warren Gatland stamping his mark on the tour. Warburton is his man. He was always a reluctant captain in the first place and needed considerable persuasion from Gatland to take the role for Wales in the 2011 Rugby World Cup. The recent RBS Six Nations was difficult for him, resulting in his not captaining against England even when stand-in skipper Ryan Jones was injured. But on the day he still led magnificently and managed a rapport with referee Steve Walsh that England captain Robshaw could not manage. It is Warburton’s first tour and he would have to deal with former captains in O’Driscoll and O’Connell, but he was Wales captain at the age of 22 after all, and should not be cowed by their presence. Related Articles
Zebo intent on marvellous mischief
26 Apr 2013
Warburton to captain Lions
27 Apr 2013
Telfer's 'Everest' Lions speech
08 Feb 2013
Lynagh: O'Connell for Lions captain
25 Apr 2013
Gatland: I will keep squad secret
25 Apr 2013
Ashton makes late play for Lions
24 Apr 2013
Accusations of favouritism One problem might be that Gatland’s party is perceived as being too Welsh. Of the possible 38-man squad, as many as 15 could be Welsh, with prop Paul James a 16th possibility. And the appointment of Neil Jenkins last week added to Gatland, Rob Howley as coaches, as well as analysts Rhys Long and Rhodri Bown, plus medical performance manager Prav Mathema and head of physical performance Adam Beard. It is possible this could cause some grumbles elsewhere - especially in England - but then again Wales have won the Six Nations for the last two seasons. Back row This is the trickiest of areas, where there are a plethora of candidates and possible combinations. The first thing to say is that the selectors are probably fortunate that Ireland’s Stephen Ferris is injured and therefore unavailable. When both fully fit only a cigarette paper can separate him and Wales’ Dan Lydiate as the finest blindside flanker in Britain and Ireland. As it is, a gamble may have to be taken on Lydiate’s fitness. He has appeared just four times for Newport Gwent Dragons (two full matches) since returning from long-term injury, but Gatland is known to be a huge admirer of his chop tackling and general work rate. Lydiate has put on half a stone of muscle while injured and was outstanding in the Dragons’ win over Munster last weekend. For all the talk of genuine opensides and the like, any back row selection is all about balance. Warburton works best at openside with Lydiate at blindside, and with Toby Faletau as a powerful carrier in between. The option of Warburton and Justin Tipuric together, so effective against England, will be considered, but Tipuric’s ball skills and vision are more likely to be deployed in last quarters. It is believed that the selectors are keen to utilise Robshaw’s admirable leadership qualities and work rate but finding a place for him will be tricky. Sean O’Brien, equally adept at open or blind, is almost certain to travel, and Tom Croft is considered a better option than Robshaw at blindside. England’s Tom Wood and Scotland’s Kelly Brown look likely to miss out. At No 8 England’s Ben Morgan would surely have been pushing for a place had he played a full Six Nations. Indeed Ireland’s Heaslip can consider himself fortunate to be going given his recent indifferent form, but go he probably will. Props The biggest question is how many to take. Gethin Jenkins (who may have to fly out to Australia after the French Top 14 final on June 1), Adam Jones, Cian Healy and Dan Cole would appear to be certainties, but thereafter problems arise. Euan Murray or Mike Ross as an extra tighthead? Paul James arguably deserves a spot as someone who can play both sides of the scrummage. But should Gatland gamble on Mako Vunipola’s raw power in the loose or - an even greater risk - Alex Corbisiero’s fitness? And then there is Ryan Grant’s all-round attributes, which make him a candidate. Inside centre/utility player The Lions coaches mentioned Billy Twelvetrees long ago in briefings as a possibile selection and his place will be debated hard on Monday. He can cover fly-half, something Scotland’s Greig Laidlaw could do from scrum half. James Hook, not especially rated by Gatland, is unlikely to make it. But it is cover for Jamie Roberts at inside centre that is most needed. And in that regard Scotland’s Matt Scott, England’s Brad Barritt and Ireland’s Gordon D’Arcy look likely to be disappointed. Wings George North and Alex Cuthbert are going, and it will be a surprise if Tommy Bowe does not join them. After that it is uncertain. Wasps’ Christian Wade has his proponents but defensive frailties linger too strongly and the truth is that Gloucester’s Jonny May is probably ahead of him, even in England terms. England’s other wingers can forget it. Scotland’s Tim Visser and Sean Maitland, and Ireland’s Craig Gilroy also have question marks beside their names. Had Simon Zebo been fit throughout the Six Nations you suspect there would not be so much argument. Probable squad Full backs: Leigh Halfpenny (Wales), Stuart Hogg (Scotland), Rob Kearney (Ireland)
